d"},"en":{"about 1075–29 June 1161":"about 1075–29 June 1161","1080–1165":"1080–1165","1108–1129":"1108–1129","1075–1161":"1075–1161","1129":"1129","1080":"1080","about 1129":"about 1129","about 1108":"about 1108","1165":"1165","1075":"1075","1161":"1161","about 1075":"about 1075","29 June 1161":"29 June 1161","1108":"1108","Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England","Parham Castle, Plomesgate, Sussex, England.":"Parham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Valognes,Manche,Basse-Normandy,France.":"Valognes, Cherbourg-Octeville, Manche, Lower Normandy, France","Ellenhall Manor, Raunton, Staffordshire":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Count Robert I Valognes was born about 1075, in Valognes, Cherbourg-Octeville, Manche, Lower Normandy, France. He had at least 1 son with Countess Agnes de Lacy. He died on 29 June 1161, in Parham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 87."},"et":{"about 1075–29 June 1161":"umbes 1075–2